            				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
            			      		<marginalia_text>
            			      			P. Ceualerius, Ciuis Geneuensis, idemq[ue] magnus religionis,
            			      		</marginalia_text>
            				 	<person name="Pierre Chevalier"/>
            			      		<location name="Geneva"/>
            				</position>
        				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						et Hebraica[e] lingua[e] professor, mihi sa[e]p&egrave; solebat dicere: ) Veni
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						) Domine: Eamus
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						in campos ad ridendu[m]. Cum prim&ugrave;m autem in campis essemus, 
        						statim sine
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						vlla causa ridebat Stentoric&egrave;.
        						Nec cessabat altissima exclamatione ridere, 
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						vt insanus; donec spiritus
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						deficeret. Ha-ha-ha. Hi-hi-hi. Ho-ho-ho. Ha-hi-ho. Nec 
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						finem ullum faciebat, donec
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						fer&egrave; rumperetur. Nunq[uam] vidi talem Pygma[e]um,
        						tantum agere in ridendo Gygantem.
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        			</language>
        			<translation>
        				Pierre Chevalier, citizen of Geneva and great professor of the Hebrew religion and language, 
        				often used to tell me: ) Come, master, Let's go to the fields to laugh. But were we to be	<!-- CG: I'm unclear what "the fields" are. --><!--JG: Don't know either, but I think it's correct to translate it as fields-->
        				first in the fields, at once, without any reason, he would begin to howl with laughter.
        				And he wouldn't stop laughing in loud cries, as if possessed, until he ran out of breath. 
        				Ha-ha-ha. Hi-hi-hi. Ho-ho-ho. Ha-hi-ho. And he didn't stop, until he had
        				nearly collapsed. Never did I see a Pygmy stir a giant so much to laughter. 
        			</translation>
        		</marginalia>
    		
